What is counted? The ČSSD in Prague knows neither Voldemort nor the pastry shop
The new ČSSD councilors in the capital are apparently going to have to overcome the obvious language barriers in order for the members of the Prague Board and the Municipal Council to understand their renewed colleagues from the ODS.
The Aktuálně.cz period &quot;tested&quot; the members of the new ČSSD Council to check their knowledge of the marked slang language that has emerged in recent years in the Council, when the current members of the coalition ruled Prague.
Mayor Pavel Bém&#39;s coded dictionary used by the political cream of Prague during the previous period includes some of the most well-known characters, situations and causes of the metropolis.
Surprisingly, it has been found that the new councilors hardly understand these familiar concepts.
At least that&#39;s what they say.
&quot;Who is Voldemort?&quot;
&quot;The truth is that I do not know.&quot;
&quot;I am more of a novice in Prague politics,&quot; said Councilor for Culture Lukáš Kaucký during the &quot;collegueo&quot; terminology test.
And as for the veteran politician, Karel Březina reacted the same.
You may be familiar with the term &quot;golf hole.&quot;
&quot;Possibly the only expression of all the ones you asked me that I use from time to time.&quot;
&quot;If not, I don&#39;t normally use slang.&quot;
From the glossary, whose definitions were published by the newspaper Aktuálně.cz last June before the ODS voting congress, the editorial staff chose six examples, in particular those that are especially related to the municipal authorities of Prague.
The Socialists had to explain the concepts &quot;Voldemort&quot;, &quot;Prague&#39;s biggest golf hole&quot;, &quot;go to the bakery&quot;, &quot;nape of the bull&quot;, &quot;treason of the capital&quot; and &quot;shield&quot;.
Three councilors agreed to take the test and a fourth, Antonín Weinert, who will be responsible for education in Prague in the future, agreed at first, but did not pick up the phone again.
The fifth councilor, Petr Dolínek, directly refused to do so.
&quot;I am not getting into these things and I am not going to assess how much fun civic democrats have.&quot;
&quot;What I do care is how we understand each other in the execution of our programs,&quot; he said.
As has been seen, the councilor Lukáš Kaucký allegedly did not realize that the above title is an expression about an influential businessman and a friend of former mayor Bém, Roman Janoušek.
To Kaucký the word &quot;Voldemort&quot; does not say anything; the only term that got the test right is &quot;the largest golf hole in Prague.&quot;
&quot;It is about the Blanka tunnel,&quot; says Kaucký, who immediately adds: &quot;But rather I know from the news.&quot;
&quot;I&#39;m going to have to sign up for a language course,&quot; he jokes.
Karel Březina is not the only one who recognizes the Blanka tunnel on the golf hole, but also the Councilor for the Environment Lukáš Plachý.
Afterwards, both socio-democrats know who Voldemort really is and Lukáš Plachý even knows where to find that character; furthermore, he suspects the meaning of &quot;going to the pastry shop.&quot;
&quot;I think it means going to a company in Prague&quot;; Plachý is soon revealed to be the headquarters of the Janoušek companies.
Like Březina, he indicates that such knowledge was obtained from the news, but that he does not use such vocabulary.
According to the test participants, there is no such familiar glossary of colloquial terms among socio-democrats.
&quot;I asked my companions, but it really seems like we don&#39;t have anything like it.&quot;
&quot;Rather, between us we use nicknames, sometimes abbreviations or we make puns on the names,&quot; says the president of the Prague ČSSD, Petr Hulínský, whose party colleagues call Hulda.
&quot;At school they called me Bříza, but I don&#39;t know if my classmates also call me that,&quot; confesses her own nickname Karel Březina.
The Aktuálně.cz newspaper put the name to the test and it works.
To his party colleagues, Weinert is Děda (similar to &quot;yayo&quot;) or, less friendly, Dědek (&quot;old&quot;), the representative Miroslav Poche, with whom they associated before the elections hoaxes during the sponsorship of the party, receives the nickname of &quot;Igráček&quot; (&quot;playmobil&quot;) on the part of some of its companions.
Nicknames are also the only expressions that socio-democrats tolerate in speech within the party.
Hulínský does not like to be called Hulda, but the Aktuálně.cz newspaper even discovered other nicknames for this Prague president.
&quot;The baton rights doctor&quot; seems to recall that Petr Hulínský obtained his doctorate in law from the Bratislava Police Academy.
The Government wants to limit the torture of &quot;witches&quot;, as published in a brochure
Women considered as witches in Burkina Faso share certain characteristics.
They are often elderly, cannot work, for example for health reasons, are single and have no children.
Women who &quot;become&quot; witches are sent to an isolated area, so that they do not harm the rest of the town.
&quot;Men seldom suffer such fate.&quot;
&quot;Healthy young women are not isolated either, because they help with work and have children,&quot; explains a nun who, in the capital of the West African state Burkina Faso, takes care of more than 100 women expelled from their communities in a special residence .
The local government has decided to oppose this unusual &quot;social measure&quot;.
It issued an information leaflet that should help prevent witch hunts.
However, this has a downside.
&quot;More than 70% of adults in Burkina Faso cannot read,&quot; warns the Die Standard newspaper about the disadvantages of writing awareness.
Accusations of witchcraft are also common in other African countries.
In Gana, Burkina Faso&#39;s neighboring country, Ammy Hemmah, 72, was killed last week when three women and two men tortured her, covered her with gasoline and burned her.
The news appeared on the BBC.
The authors claim that it was due to an unfortunate set of circumstances.
According to his version, the woman caught herself in the oil that is used for ritual anointing.
It was set on fire when the group wanted to &quot;drive out evil spirits&quot; from the woman.
The isolation of the &quot;witches&quot; is supported by people of all educational levels.
Der Standard newspaper quoted a 42-year-old businessman from Burkina Faso: &quot;Eaters of human souls always posed a danger,&quot; he said.
While in Burkina Faso the government tries to quell the witch hunt, in Gambia last year the president was still involved.
&quot;The Gambian president Jammeh, after the death of his aunt, launched a wide hunt for the witches who, supposedly, had been related to his death and had tried to kill the president himself by means of black magic.&quot;
&quot;To help him he brought shamans from nearby Guinea who, protected by police, military and the president&#39;s personal escort, forcibly took men and women randomly chosen from among the Gambian peoples onto the president&#39;s property in Kanilai,&quot; he says in his report the organization Amnesty International.
At the farm, the arrested people had to drink a herbal potion with hallucinogenic effects, which also caused intestinal and kidney problems.
Two of those arrested did not survive their stay at the farm.
After international pressure, they finally released around a thousand detained people.
Bakala&#39;s tenant: heats himself with coal stoves and signs a higher rent
The old and sturdy man walked through the doors of the customer service center of the RPG Byty company of &quot;coal magnate&quot; Zdeňek Bakala, the largest private owner of rental flats in the Czech Republic.
Under his arm he carried some documents with the new three-story rental contracts: his, his daughter&#39;s and his son&#39;s, who is serving sentence.
All three have just been caught by rent liberalization.
Instead of 3,500 CZK a month, the son will pay from next year 4,100 CZK for a two-room apartment with a separate second-rate kitchen.
&quot;In addition, it does not have hot water and the heating is based on a solid fuel boiler,&quot; the man shows with his finger in his son&#39;s new contract, over whose signature he has full powers.
&quot;But I signed it,&quot; he explains half angry, half resigned.
The civil association BytyOKD.cz, which described the new rental conditions as &quot;incorrect and indecent&quot;, recommends tenants not to sign the new contracts and to wait until December 7, when it will publish a guide informing about how proceed in these cases.
But, faced with this, the man only makes a gesture.
&quot;Everyone says one thing,&quot; he says with a frown.
Ostrava is emerging as a large liberalization testing laboratory.
After the New Year, it will happen with the vast majority of the flats that, in the Czech Republic, were up to now under a regulated rent.
That is why Aktuálně.cz decided to visit the &quot;laboratory&quot; in person.
The RPG mining waiting room is one of four in Ostrava, and by Tuesday at nine, it was already full.
Right next to the doors are the security guards and next to them a machine to take number.
&quot;Rent 2011&quot;, can be read on a light button on its touch screen.
When pressed, a piece of paper with a number comes out of the machine.
There is hardly time to even read &quot;157&quot; and the number appears on the large screen at the top of the room.
In a second, you are in the queue.
Soon after, an elderly couple arrives to ask, but the crowd in the room is not here because of the new rents.
Most people come to solve common problems, as in the old days: repair requests, insurance questions and the like.
The letters with the new rental contracts will arrive in Ostrava in the mailboxes of the tenants of most of the 44,000 flats owned by RPG around mid-November.
RPG Byty offers you in the letters a rent increase of between 15 and 38%.
On November 18 a special window opens in the customer service center for new rentals.
&quot;It&#39;s been running for a week, so it&#39;s starting,&quot; the workers who are in it when the client introduces himself as a journalist respond, after a brief hesitation.
Liberalization and the former Bakala mining flats are the most sensitive issues in the area.
Before the elections, they were discussed loud and clear by the Ostrava deputy speaker of the Parliament, Lubomír Zaorálek, of the ČSSD, and now they appear continuously in the newspapers in the area.
&quot;Twenty years later I want a new floor.&quot;
&quot;They didn&#39;t even change my damn bathroom plate,&quot; says the man mentioned in the introduction.
According to the workers, at the moment retirees are mostly coming to see if they receive a rent discount if they sign on time, as the RPG special offer promises.
The remaining tenants who sign the new contract before December 15 will also receive half the discount on the February rent.
However, the window of mining &quot;liberalization&quot; certainly fails to dispel the avalanche of doubts.
&quot;Of the 360 clients who were here yesterday, only about forty or fifty people asked about the rent in 2011,&quot; estimates the clerk at the window.
Meanwhile, RPG proposes on the web and on its boards to hold individual meetings on contracts when necessary.
If the two parties cannot agree on the rental, an independent judge must resolve the matter.
&quot;It is not a threat, but information on the only possible way to proceed and completely in accordance with the law,&quot; RPG warns on its pages.
&quot;No one is going to be judged here&quot;, says one of the RPG Byty employees and a man who is on the street in front of the customer service center agrees, at least in part, with the reason.
&quot;I receive a pension of 13,000 and I have 5,000 left for food; I have no means to go to court,&quot; he says.
But, immediately, the employee sows doubt.
&quot;We&#39;ll see&quot;.
&quot;Mr. Zaorálek warns them in the media not to sign, so maybe people wait,&quot; he says.
Rent regulation will cease to exist in most of the Czech Republic at the beginning of 2011 and, according to RPG Byty, its increase is an economic necessity.
&quot;The current rents still do not even cover the amounts necessary for the maintenance of the community fund,&quot; recalls Pavel Klimeš, director of the residential portfolio of the company RPG Byty, adding that the neglected state of the community fund is annoying to tenants is, for landlords, the main reason to increase the rent.
While during the five years that elapsed between 2005 and 2010 RPG was able to invest four billion in apartments with rents, in the four years that will go from 2011 to 2014 the figure will increase to 5.2 billion.
The large screen that hangs from the ceiling, in front of the seats in the waiting room, now repeats some data that is highlighted in red.
&quot;The rent increase in 2011 by 15% and less applies to 31,200 apartments, that is, more than 90% of RPG properties.&quot;
&quot;In addition, it will always be a maximum of 7.50 CZK per month per square meter,&quot; is indicated on the screen.
It only increased the rent of 400 flats in RPG&#39;s portfolio by 38%.
&quot;In such cases, this is an increase from extremely low amounts of 19.66 crowns per square meter,&quot; says RPG.
In 2,600 apartments, the rent will remain unchanged next year.
RPG Byty promises that liberalization will not hit rents all at once, but will escalate over four to eight years.
In addition, add the following commitment: the company will invest all the money from the rent increase (see the graph) again in the flats, mainly in savings in heating: new windows and heating.
People who sign the rent increase agreement will have priority.
The architects have understood that offices also need a nursery
The Avriopoint administrative building in Brno is the new headquarters of the Arch.Design company.
No one would say that it also hides a small nursery with everything that is typical of such facilities: colored walls, creative furniture and even a miniature park on the outdoor terrace.
Since October last year, the children of Arch.Design employees can attend.
The architectural project company Arch.Design, from whose studio many well-known Brno buildings emerged, thought from the first sketches of the Avriopoint building to include a space for its mini-nursery.
Around 90 people work in the company, mainly in the baby boom age and they wanted to allow the architects and draftsmen to return to work soon after motherhood.
Along with the possibility of enjoying reduced hours, the nursery is one of the benefits that Arch.Design offers its employees as part of its social program.
Construction companies and architects thus have the possibility of combining a demanding profession with childcare.
The mini-nursery was the brainchild of Arch.Designu&#39;s own employees and, with the support of the management, they managed to obtain funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labor and Social Affairs.
The company&#39;s mini-nursery is financed through the European Social Fund within the framework of the Human Resources and Employment Operational Program, as well as the state budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to the financing granted (an endowment of more than 2.8 million CZK) they were able to buy the equipment and, after two years, hire qualified personnel and services.
When the funding runs out (two years), Arch.Design is required to keep the mini-nursery running with its own funds for three years.
The preparation of the project lasted one year and the Economy Rating company contributed in the presentation of the financing request.
The care of children is in the hands of qualified personnel; Furthermore, a nurse and a teacher from the Ministry of Education are present all day for their care. The nursery currently welcomes children with no age limit, although most of them are under three years of age.
Given that it is a &quot;mini-nursery&quot;, it can only accommodate a maximum of five children simultaneously, although with shifts they come more during the day.
The operation of the nursery is flexible to adapt to the needs of parents and children of all workers have the same right to use the nursery, regardless of the hierarchy within the company.
Although it is about individual teaching and care, the contents of the mini-nursery program are comparable to the usual preschool program.
In it, children not only play, but also receive quality education: from basic learning to preparation for school, they even teach English.
The class not only has toys and board games, but also a computer for the children.
The presence of young children in the company itself create a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can visit their children at any time and avoid the stress of picking up children late from school when away from work.
Thus, parents are more productive while working.
Not surprisingly, this naturally creates a loyal relationship between the worker and his employer.
In this way, Arch.Design ranks among the firms that offer a great advantage for the admission of new workers: they support the family and, ultimately, this program strengthened the marketing of personnel.
The house of bones continues to fascinate after 100 years. Take a look at Gaudí&#39;s interiors
The roof resembles the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs resemble the column of a dinosaur, and the balconies resemble the mouth of an open fish.
This is the Casa Batlló, in Barcelona, of the Catalan architect Antoni Gaudí.
Due to its skeleton-like shape, locals nicknamed it &quot;the house of bones.&quot;
Its organic forms, its striking colors, the novel use of stone, fragments of tiles and mosaics, a façade reminiscent of scales and the omnipresent gently curved lines, all this is typical of Antoni Gaudí&#39;s secession.
The front of the house plays with dream lines, delicate colors and textures taken from nature and fauna.
Paying more attention, a certain geometry, rhythm and a carefully thought out order are observed.
At night, the entire facade of the house looks even more impressive, since it is illuminated in such a way that the brightness of the colors is enhanced.
It meanders and the twisting of the forms continues to surprise us also inside.
Corrugated wood copies window frames, railings, door trim, peepholes, and signs.
Casa Batlló, which is located in the Eixample neighborhood at number 43 on the lively shopping street of Passeig de Grácia, arose from the remodeling of a house from 1877 by the architect Emilio Sala Cortés.
Reconstruction took two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, initially insisted on tearing down the old building and starting from scratch, but soon accepted Gaudí&#39;s idea of a new and cheaper reconstruction.
However, the Casa Batlló, made up of various apartments, was not designed by Antoni Gaudí alone.
The architect Josep María Jujol collaborated in the design.
In fact, ornaments for the property owner&#39;s representative apartment and mosaics used on the façade emerged from their project plans.
On the facade also workers other creators and artists.
Collaboration on the Casa Batlló proposals was the beginning of Jujol&#39;s successful collaboration with Gaudí.
Jujol participated in the construction of Casa Milá and Gaudí&#39;s Güell Park, which houses other pieces of it.
Due to its organic form, locals shortly after its completion dubbed it &quot;the house of bones.&quot;
Others, due to the specific mechanism of opening the windows, began to call it &quot;the house of yawns&quot;.
It is also said that, at the top of the building, appears the sword of Saint George, the patron saint of Catalonia.
Other sculptural elements of the construction hide religious motifs.
Gaudí designed in the house a unique system for the time of central heating with ventilation vents and the typical chimneys.
Its 45 degree tilt may be strange.
During the construction, Gaudí did not respect the construction regulations of the time at all and was not influenced by them.
Even so, the construction obtained the corresponding permit from the beginning, although evidently in it the data indicated on the planned reconstruction were so vague that, two years later, at its completion, the city council was so shocked with the result that it requested that it be correct.
It bothered him, for example, that the building included columns even down to the public sidewalk.
The arrangements were never made, quite the contrary: just fifteen days after the request of the city council, Josep Batlló requested (and obtained) permission to rent the two highest floors of the building.
The owner himself settled on the lower floors.
On the second floor gallery was the living room and on the third floor the bedrooms and the private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewelry store.
The six-story house is completely traversed by a staircase that leads to the roof terrace.
The basic elements of the reform consisted of breaking all the angles and straight lines, covering them with curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with the modern concept of space connection.
The common part can be completely connected by opening the doors of the rooms and a larger group can communicate in this way without problems, without giving up the privacy necessary for more intimate conversations.
The house, with Gaudí&#39;s reconstruction, not only got a new facade, but also an unusual roof and two additional floors.
It is also impressive how Gaudí plays with light, white and blue tiles that cover the interior patio and skylights.
The game with the two colors provides maximum light on all floors of the house.
It was based simply on the principle that white reflects more light than dark colors, which on the contrary absorb the sun&#39;s rays.
Anyone can visit Casa Batlló, which in 2005 was added to the UNESCO World Heritage List.
On the first floor of the house is the largest and most ornate apartment accessible to the public.
The owners decided to open the doors to the public in 2002, on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the famous creator&#39;s birth.
With the visits they confirmed, or discovered, that it is a very profitable business and extended the visits to the common area and the loft, including the roof terrace.
The entrance price to the monument is not insignificant, it reaches 16.50 euros, although students, pensioners and holders of tourist cards get a 20% discount.
The amount considerably exceeds the price of admission to other Gaudí buildings in the city.
