How to choose the mattress and the box spring: women and men look for different things
No pompous frame for the bed; what really gives a good bed its quality is the surface to lie on, that is, the mattress and the bed base.
Above all, they must complement each other perfectly to suit specific users.
Numerous elements come into play during the choice, including the owner&#39;s weight, height, health, and gender.
The type of interior in which the mattress and box spring are located is also important.
A typical example?
For example, in a weekend cabin that is not typically heated, latex mattresses should not be used because they &quot;heat up&quot; more slowly.
In addition, they tend to weigh considerably more than regular polyurethane mattresses.
Therefore, it is necessary to turn them more frequently.
If the channels in the center are not adequately aerated and, above, they are on a firm base, they keep moisture inside. Mold can even appear underneath.
When choosing a bed, customs also play a role.
Anyone who has spent a lot of time abroad often uses a very high mattress with a soft underlay and will have trouble feeling good on a lower, harder surface.
&quot;Almost all the hockey players who came back from the NHL complained that they didn&#39;t sleep as well here.&quot;
&quot;For their crushed shoulders, heels and hips they needed mattresses with a soft memory foam layer.&quot;
&quot;This type of mattress is also recommended for people with diabetes who suffer from nervous system problems, which is why they receive poor information from the joints and the skin,&quot; explains Sylva Hadamcziková, who specializes in upholstered furniture.
Memory foam mattresses have long been preferred by many hockey players, as well as other customers.
&quot;Today there is no problem, because they have these suitable Tempur and the Italian Magniflex, but also the Czech brand Tropico.&quot;
You no longer have to be an NHL player to appreciate memory foam.
This &quot;miracle&quot; works in a very simple way.
Optimizes its stiffness and shape based on absorbed heat or adapts to your body heat.
Nothing exerts pressure; During the night, it will not spin like after a hard game.
You just sleep better.
The memory foam also works as protection against sores.
When choosing the size of the mattress, add to its height the length of your feet, that is, between 21 and 34 cm.
A man or woman with a height of around 180 cm will need a bed between 210 and 220 cm.
The minimum width for one person should be, in a double room, 90 cm, in total 180 cm.
In the case of individual rooms, for example single rooms, a minimum of 120-140 cm is recommended.
So that a possible visit is also comfortable.
&quot;If not, a simple rule can be applied to calculate the width: when lying on your back, you should keep your hands comfortably tucked towards your elbows,&quot; advises engineer Helena Prokopová, an expert from Cechu čalouníků a dekoratérů, who has been working for many years. of the problem of healthy sleep and the ergonomics of furniture, a subject taught in specialized schools.
In the double rooms, everyone needs their own bed base and mattress, so during the purchase you have to pay attention to match the height of the mattresses.
Otherwise, it will be necessary to mount the bed bases at different heights, which is not always possible on all beds.
The foam mattresses should have a minimum height of 14 cm, the models with interior springs a minimum of 15 cm, of which at least three centimeters are for the layer that adapts to the shapes and softens.
&quot;When you touch it with your hand or when you sit on the mattress, you should definitely not feel the springs,&quot; says Helena Prokopová.
Each mattress requires a specific type of bed base.
Fully padded bedrooms, in which the mattress and base are like Siamese twins, make no sense in the bedroom.
Mattresses breathe badly and their covers cannot be washed, which is often done today.
And, given that every night we perspire between 0.2 and 0.75 liters of sweat, it is clear that after five or seven years the mattress will begin to remind us of a large (and congested) sieve.
For this reason, specialists reject slogans that speak of a mattress life of up to 25 years or even a lifetime guarantee.
However, everything has a but.
Therefore, the sellers give a tip: on mattresses with a width of 120 or 140 cm, take care of the cleaning and washing of the cover carefully, but better add a mattress protector that can be easily removed and washed.
Although mattress covers with zipper closure are currently manufactured around their perimeter, so when they are opened they remain in two parts (something very important for washing and the size of the washing machine!), Their handling in larger models size (and by one person) when lifting the mattress it can seem like a fight between a flyweight and a heavyweight.
In bed, instead of a box spring, do you have a firm board?
Never!
At most for the beds designed for visitors to spend one night.
However, it should make (if you don&#39;t already have them) ventilation holes in the board and it should be used with a mattress with springs inside and a minimum height of 15 cm with the springs in bags (like the German Taschenfederkern) and a layer soft.
Polyurethane mattresses should not be used on such bases.
Latex mattresses or sandwich mattresses (for example, a combination of latex and coconut fiber) can be used for non-articulating slatted beds containing between 14 and 18 slats, although a bed base with a greater number of mattresses is always better. laminae, 28 or more, in which the laminae of the lumbar area are reinforced and their stiffness can be regulated.
Articulating slatted bases should not be used with a spring mattress, as it does not react to recline.
In addition to adjusting the stiffness of the slats, you can also use shoulder protection.
It is a special fixation of the slats that allows the slats to be pressed or even tilted in such a way that they perfectly &quot;surround&quot; the shoulders during sleep.
For men with very broad shoulders, this is very important.
Even mattress manufacturers remember them, who, in the &quot;male&quot; ones, began to use a softer area precisely around the shoulders.
They also remember women, for whom they put a softer area around the hips.
For the most demanding clients, there are slatted or cross-structure bed bases with so-called multi-torsion damping.
The pressure is distributed between different points and the tension is lowered.
You should also keep in mind that even if you use the right mattress and box spring, if you use a bad pillow (large and &quot;fluffy&quot;), most of the benefits will disappear.
The basic rule is simple: the pillow should support the head and the corners can only reach up to the shoulders, so that the muscles of the shoulders can relax.
The recommended suitable size is 50 x 60 cm, which is normal for example in Scandinavia.
When lying on your side, the pillow should be at the same level (when combined with the box spring with shoulder bolster or the softest area of the mattress) as shoulder height.
Modern mattresses seem to have something to do with original straw-filled mattresses.
Manufacturers continue to use, more and more often, natural materials or, at least, mixtures.
In fact, biological mattresses are in fashion.
The petroleum-based raw materials, from which the polyurethane foam is made, are filled with natural oils, for example castor or soy.
In fact, practically all known manufacturers use soybeans.
&quot;Biological, in the case of mattresses, means that the center is made only of materials of natural origin&quot;, explains Petr Vašíček of the company Tropico Plus.
Likewise, natural substances are used during the manufacture of mattress covers, one of the first aloe vera.
But you can also opt for microcapsules, which release a fresh scent of forest or lavender.
There are also differences for men and women.
While men are &quot;cooled&quot; with breeze plant extracts, so that the mattress cover absorbs heat and refreshes the body, women prefer to &quot;heat&quot; the cover.
Red pepper extract improves blood circulation, so that women feel more warm.
The current favorites?
Mattresses made of cold foam, which are more porous, with an adapted cell structure, which makes them more permeable than normal polyurethane and offer more permeability.
The combination of various cold and memory foam rigidities allows for the manufacture of multi-zone mattresses that know exactly where the head, shoulders and heels are going.
A good quality mattress will cost you seven thousand crowns and up.
Those that perform a therapeutic function tend to have a lower VAT, since they are considered as health means.
The first to gain this advantage in the Czech Republic was Gumotex.
It is difficult to save on mattresses and box springs.
Sometimes you can approve offers from manufacturers or sellers, who sometimes offer two mattresses for the price of one.
For example, the Magniflex brand offers Duofreeze mattresses with a memory foam attached to the cover for 11,990 crowns.
The second is obtained free of charge.
The era of viscoelastic with an open cell structure and high density began with the &quot;cosmic&quot; material from Tempur.
Initially it emerged as material for NASA, because during takeoffs the astronauts were subjected to an enormous overload.
Tempur softens in heat and hardens in cold.
Consequently, the warm human body exerts a perfect effect and optimally adapts its pressure.
Therefore, it is ideal to prevent sores from occurring, but also to improve comfort during sleep.
Memory foam is not only used in mattresses, but also for sanitary products, for example for pillows that are placed under the legs and relieve them, as well as their circulation.
Domestic manufacturers, for example, use Eucatherm C or Twinsaver foam and the like.
More and more parents are using people tracking devices to monitor their children
Fear for children leads more and more people to think about controlling them by GPS.
The system, initially designed for vehicle tracking, can also follow the movement of people and thus contribute, for example, in the case of the disappearance of the nine-year-old Anička Janatková.
At the moment the device is about the size of a matchbox, but it will soon be reduced to the size of a clock.
Many people were afraid of the case of the missing Anička and began to inform themselves about the means available to better protect their children.
Even at the cost of invading your privacy.
&quot;We are all trying to tell ourselves that it is not about spying, but about another means to reduce the chances of a tragedy,&quot; says Petr Pilin from Macro Weil, one of the providers of tracking devices in the Czech market.
&quot;I recognize that, in certain cases, such devices can be abused, for example if they are put in someone&#39;s bag without their knowledge, but we have not come across such cases yet.&quot;
&quot;Most customers actually buy it for security reasons,&quot; adds Pilin.
In his opinion, children should always know what the &quot;box&quot; is for and how it is used in an emergency.
Child psychologist Dana Bočková warns about the fact that if the child does not want to carry it, he will simply throw it away.
&quot;Even the youngest children show great creativity in intentionally losing certain things if they want to avoid being controlled.&quot;
&quot;Before, parents relied heavily on mobiles, but they could be turned off as easily as the tracking device,&quot; says Bočková.
In his opinion, it is debatable whether such a device is really useful in the event of an attack.
&quot;If it is a prepared kidnapping, the perpetrator will practically always check if the child is carrying some type of electronic device that can reveal his location.&quot;
&quot;Now it&#39;s the phone.&quot;
&quot;As the use of tracking devices becomes more widespread, it will also look for them, since their sale will undoubtedly be done with a lot of publicity.&quot;
&quot;In such cases, criminals are always one step ahead of the police,&quot; says the psychologist.
However, he adds that such devices can help in the event of an impromptu pedophile attack.
According to Robert Čech of the company RC Monitoring, which offers tracking services for both vehicles and people, even if the tracking device is immediately destroyed after an attack, their presence can help.
&quot;You can configure the device to send the position regularly after a certain period.&quot;
&quot;If it suffers damage, it will at least facilitate the last position of the person in question.&quot;
&quot;The more expensive devices have a built-in tilt meter, so if the person simply slips and becomes immobile, the device will immediately issue a warning with the position in question,&quot; says Čech.
In his opinion, such a service can be obtained even with smart mobile phones with navigation, in which only special software has to be installed.
The problem with current monitoring units is that at the moment they are devices with a size similar to a matchbox or smaller mobile phones.
Therefore, they can be lost.
According to Pilin of Macro Weil, for that reason, tests are currently being carried out with devices that look like a digital watch.
&quot;In addition, they will have the added advantage that a potential attacker may not identify the device.&quot;
&quot;Or to identify him after a certain time, which can save the police time,&quot; he adds.
Whether the tracking devices are worn on the wrist or hanging, they will still use the same technology used for vehicle tracking.
It involves checking the position with a GPS system (used in normal car navigation) combined with the function of a mobile phone that communicates the current position.
The army has enough fuses to encircle the whole of the Czech Republic. But they only last two years
The Czech army bought 445 kilometers of fuse to ignite explosives.
Last year the Ministry of Defense added 224 kilometers of fuse to its arsenal.
Therefore, they have stocks for 225 years.
The problem is that the useful life of the wick is two years, four at the most.
The army bought the explosives fuse from the STV Group for 40 million kronor.
The General&#39;s staff responded to MF DNES justifying the purchase of such an enormous quantity of match saying that soldiers need 60 kilometers of match per year for training maneuvers.
According to the calculations of the army pyrotechnicians, with whom MF DNES contacted, however, it is decided that, in such a case, all generals, high command officers, should carry out such maneuvers with frequent use of explosives every year. and even secretaries and cleaners.
Neither Defense Minister Alexandr Vondr nor Army Captain Vlastimil Picek wanted to be exempted.
Only in this way could it be justified that the army wasting sixty kilometers of fuse.
Such a length is equivalent to 25,000 explosions.
Even if that were the case, the army would have enough supplies to last more than ten years.
If on the contrary, as the experts say, for the initial training of each new professional arrives with a maximum of two meters of fuse, the army would have with the new purchase (even adding the consumption of the engineering or special units) sufficient stocks for the 225 listed above.
Soldiers from the rapid intervention brigade recently complained personally to Minister Vondra because they say they have little ammunition for various weapons, so even target practice is limited for money.
And let&#39;s not talk about the lack of underwear.
&quot;I also cannot understand why they repeatedly buy such quantities of wick from us.&quot;
&quot;But it is their decision and they will undoubtedly know why they act this way.&quot;
&quot;For us, the army is a good customer that, as a company, we try to satisfy,&quot; admits STV Group commercial director Jan Děcký.
Defense Ministry spokesman Jan Pejšek defends the hundreds of kilometers of match, also saying that he will have a stock of this &quot;ammunition&quot; for at least ten years.
However, Jan Děcký from the STV Group indicates that the fuse only has a useful life of four years and, in the case of fireworks for the army or the police, two years.
&quot;If it is stored in perfect conditions, it can last up to four,&quot; says one of the soldiers who, due to possible criticism from the army, does not want to give his name.
After the end of its useful life, each ammunition must be carefully checked to see if it remains reliable and will not harm soldiers.
But these tests are not free and require an additional investment.
Another argument of the Ministry is that, when buying 445 kilometers of wick, it obtained a discount.
&quot;They cost us 60% less than last year&#39;s order for 244 kilometers,&quot; says spokesman Pejšek from the Defense Ministry&#39;s purchasing center.
Just to compare: the annual fuse consumption of the police pyrotechnics, who dispose of the ammunition of the Second World War or that left by the Soviet army, has not exceeded 1,500 meters for years.
In addition, the police always ask for only the right amount to use up the ammunition before its useful life runs out.
They decided it for safety reasons for the pyrotechnicians and, in addition, in the meantime more modern and reliable types of fuse are available.
The Ministry already has clear difficulties finishing tens of thousands of tons of ammunition from the time of the Warsaw Pact, when the 200,000-strong Czechoslovak army was preparing for a campaign on the Rhine.
According to the pyrotechnicians with whom MF DNES spoke, after a couple of years the following problem will occur with the current one: hundreds of kilometers of old wick will have to be eliminated, which is now being bought &quot;cheaply&quot;.
Until now I continue to live on the contacts I got thanks to the contest
