A poll that reveals the ridiculous rules
The Absurdez of the Year survey is part of the business tournament for the fourth time.
It has already managed to remove some ridiculous rules.
The unknown winner of the new edition of the Absurdity of the Year survey was the obligation to bring to the administration documents that officials can access online.
The decision was made by more than a third of nearly 4,000 voters.
For example, the social security administration asked for an extract from the commercial register, although its officials can obtain it with two movements of the mouse.
Thanks to the survey, this has changed.
&quot;The Czech social security administration will no longer ask for an extract from the commercial register when carrying out a check on the insured&#39;s tax,&quot; said ČSSZ spokeswoman Jana Buraňová.
The objective of the Absurdity of the Year survey is to consult the rules and regulations that businesses and entrepreneurs in the Czech Republic must respect and to try to eliminate those that are absurd.
This year it is for the fourth time part of the business tournament of the publication Hospodářské noviny and is also beginning to create fans among the general public.
While last year&#39;s edition had the participation of three thousand voters, this year it practically reached four thousand.
And it is not surprising, since we still have several legal obligations to spare that must be respected simply to trade.
&quot;Perhaps we are in first place in the number of tax returns in the world,&quot; says Karel Havlíček from the Association of small and medium-sized enterprises and entrepreneurs of the Czech Republic.
For years, simplifying business rules has been a declared goal of all governments.
However, compared to the rest of the world, the situation improves especially in the Czech Republic.
According to the World Bank, from the point of view of the conditions to have a company, the Czech Republic is ranked 74th, that is, eight places worse than last year.
The Absurdity of the Year contest was held for the first time in 2006 and is repeated every year in the same way.
Anyone can indicate some administrative or bureaucratic absurdity each year between April and the end of September, when the contest closes.
Proposals can be made on the website www.firmaroku.cz. The contest organizer then chooses seven candidates for the &quot;anti-prize&quot; and, during October, allows the public to vote online through www.firmaroku.cz/absurdita and www.ihned.cz.
The absurdity that receives the most votes wins.
For this year&#39;s survey, more than 100 were submitted, in particular 105 rules and regulations that make no sense.
The examples were sent by both businessmen, professional associations and journalists.
Among the &quot;finalists&quot; of the contest was, for example, the requirement that vehicles for the maintenance of roads and highways pay the toll or that employers with twenty employees, two offices and two bathrooms paint the walls every two years.
The list of the seventy proposals for this year is published on the pages of the contest.
The announcement of the contest, which always takes place at the beginning of November in Prague&#39;s Wenceslas Square, is part of an event in which personalities from the political and social world usually participate.
This year, for example, this competition event was attended by Eva Svobodová, director of the Association of small and medium-sized enterprises and entrepreneurs of the Czech Republic, or Petr Kužel, president of the Chamber of Commerce of the Republic.
&quot;Economic prosperity cannot be maintained if the State continually hinders businessmen, so my goal is to eliminate every year a minimum of thirty paragraphs that currently unnecessarily complicate trade&quot;, announced the Minister of Industry and Commerce Martin Kocourek .
Efforts to eliminate absurd regulations do not end in borage.
In 2007, what bothered people the most was the employer&#39;s obligation to notify the business office of the permanent operating area three days in advance of his intention to attend a fair or exhibition with a booth.
This obligation was eliminated in the new industrial law.
The obligation that finished second in number of votes in 2007, that is, the communication to the labor office by its foreign workers of work trips of up to 30 days, was eliminated in the so-called green card law. .
And the third time is the charm.
The Absurdity of 2009 was the regulation for physiotherapists to have a large mirror, a refrigerator and two floor scales in their practice.
For this reason, this year the Ministry of Health issued a communication saying that it had eliminated the obligation to have a refrigerator.
