Families will have to pay additional expenses of several hundred crowns per month
Households will have to pay from January not only for all types of energy, but also for water and electricity, heating supplements and, in some cases, higher rents.
As a result, families will have to withdraw from their wallets, from January, several hundred crowns a month more than now.
The price of electricity increases by 4.6%, gas by around 2%, in some cities they will have to pay up to 10% more for water supply and many also increase the price of central heating.
The rise in electricity for families living in apartments should amount to about 100 kronor more per year than now.
However, the main electricity providers reduced prices, due to increasing support for energy production from renewable sources, in particular photovoltaics.
However, gas becomes moderately expensive, especially at a time when heating is used more and, therefore, consumption is higher.
In this case, they should also have a couple hundred more crowns a year.
While electricity and gas are becoming more expensive across the country, the price change for central heating varies from place to place.
The price increase is mainly planned by the largest municipality.
For example, households in Pardubice or Hradec Králové will pay about 50 more crowns per month for central heating from January, while families in Liberec will pay more than 1,000 additional crowns a year.
Residents in Prague will also have to bear a 9% increase in the price of water and heating, especially if the city increases the rent for infrastructure.
If the rent remains the same, Prague residents will pay an additional 6.8%.
Prices in Prague, however, will continue to be among the lowest in the entire country.
In northern Bohemia, where current prices are among the highest, both rates will rise by 7.4%.
They can significantly increase rental prices for 450,000 rented flats in Prague, where regulation will end in January.
For example, the company CPI Byty, which owns around 2,500 flats in Ústí nad Labem, will increase the rent from January by up to 100%.
The company will take to court those who disagree with the new rent.
Regulated rents, which benefit residents of around 300,000 flats, could rise as much as 10% next year.
Young Czechs get drunk on Fernet and rum. Beer is no longer in mode, because it takes effect slowly
Fernet, rum, vodka and even good whiskeys stolen from their parents.
Those are the drinks that cause young drinkers under the age of fifteen to end up in medical care.
Children who end up lying in the hospital continually to get over a hangover are no longer an exception.
This stems from the experience of physicians who come across such cases in hospital pediatric admissions.
&quot;Drinking beer or wine is no longer in fashion, because they take a long time to get drunk.&quot;
&quot;Now the trend is strong alcoholic beverages,&quot; Luděk Pelikán, head of pediatrics at Hořovice Hospital in central Bohemia, tells Právo.
&quot;When they manage to get their father a bottle from the cupboard, it may be whiskey, but usually it&#39;s Fernet and vodka.&quot;
&quot;Vodka has the advantage that it is lightened with juice and that it doesn&#39;t smell as much,&quot; he explains.
It is also confirmed by the spokeswoman for Motol University Hospital, Eva Jurinová.
&quot;Usually this is Fernet or rum.&quot;
&quot;Those are modern alcoholic beverages, particularly among schoolchildren.&quot;
&quot;In some cases, they use brandy that they took at home,&quot; adds Jurinová.
According to Chief Pelikán, thirteen and fourteen-year-old drinkers are the ones who usually appear in hospitals.
Before Hořovice, where she has been working since this year, she worked for a decade in pediatrics in Motol, where ambulances brought young people from nearby areas.
&quot;A girl had to enter maybe four times.&quot;
&quot;It began when she was twelve years old, when they brought her with 3.5 alcohol in her blood, in addition to a mixture with ecstasy,&quot; says the department doctor about this case.
&quot;He was at the Holešovice fair at some dance party.&quot;
&quot;The interesting thing is that her mother was not surprised that her daughter disappeared 48 hours,&quot; the boss is surprised.
It is precisely the lack of interest of parents or even their clear tolerance towards drinking by their children that is considered the main cause of the increase in alcohol consumption among young people.
Experts point out that, in the case of children, one cannot properly speak of dependency.
&quot;An alcoholic is understood as a person who has been chronically dependent on alcohol for several years, with all the phenomena associated with it, which does not occur in children.&quot;
&quot;In those who repeatedly drink alcohol, it is rather due to a systematically unsuccessful social or family environment,&quot; explains Chief Pelikán.
According to spokeswoman Jurinová, this year at the Motol pediatric clinic forty drunk children were hospitalized until mid-November.
However, the statistics only show those who come with a serious poisoning and must remain in the hospital.
Young drinkers who, after the mobile medical examination, go home with their parents or the police, do not count.
In addition to the cases in which children simply meet after school and drink brandy, for Pelikán there are three seasonal ups and downs that should be mentioned: Halloween, New Year&#39;s Eve and the end of the school year.
&quot;In such circumstances, they drink because of poor grades or, on the contrary, they celebrate the beginning of the holidays.&quot;
&quot;On Halloween, I have seen up to seven drunk children in admissions at the same time,&quot; adds Pelikán.
Drinkers who spend the night in detoxification under the supervision of doctors, paradoxically, have the advantage that the next day they do not suffer a terrible hangover at home.
The morning headache, caused by dehydration and lack of glucose, is avoided with the injection of a serum with glucose and with the nutrients that the body lacks.
&quot;They wear it much better, because after a hectic night, they get up well and it doesn&#39;t hurt at all.&quot;
&quot;They are only confused about where they are,&quot; says Pelikán, adding that patients often lose their good humor at least when they see the expenses they have generated.
Transportation by ambulance and hospitalization in a room for critically ill patients cost up to ten thousand crowns.
&quot;I have often used cost as a means of educating them, when on the visit I tell the children directly how much their drunkenness has cost and that they would have to spend the whole summer in a youth job for you to earn enough to pay for that night &quot;adds Pelikán.
Health insurance, in his opinion perhaps as a regressive measure, which usually reimburses people for the costs of treatment, does not do so for children who drink.
Two L-159 planes are in the hands of others for the first time in Spain
Two L-159 aircraft out of a total of five, for which the Czech Defense Ministry replaced the Casa C-295M aircraft, departed on Tuesday for Seville, where the manufacturer of the Casa aircraft - EADS is located.
It is the first time that such a device has been in the hands of someone other than the Czech army.
At the moment, they were only abroad for practice or demonstration flights.
It is the two-seater version L-159T1, which up to now was used by the Czech army and which was still in a state of flight.
The remaining three aircraft are single-seater L-159.
These are still kept at Aer Vodochody and the intermediary for the sale, the Omnipol company, already took care of them last week.
Jan Peješk from the defense press department indicates that it is not yet known when the planes will be physically removed from Vodochody.
&quot;The single-seater L-159 planes, on the other hand, were separated from the planes repaired long ago, without investments or additional contributions from the Ministry.&quot;
&quot;The two-seater L-159T1s were exchanged in their current state,&quot; he told Právo Pejšek.
He added that the army does not run out of two-seater aircraft, since in May 2009 the army signed a contract with Aer Vodochody for an amount of 200 million crowns for the construction of four unnecessary L-159 devices for two-seaters.
One of the new aircraft was already received by the army in July, the other will be delivered by the end of the year.
According to Pejšek, EADS promised that the aircraft would be added to the equipment of some allied countries.
&quot;The contract clearly indicates that the EADS company is the one that retires the L-159 aircraft and that they will be used for the training of pilots from NATO countries.&quot;
&quot;So it is up to the buyer to decide how they are going to use them in this framework,&quot; says Pejšek.
The newspaper Hospodářské noviny published ahead of time that, for example, the Spanish army is not interested in the L-159.
The exchange of five L-159s for a Casa aircraft and the purchase of three other aircraft for 3.5 billion crowns were approved last year by the Mirek Topolánek government.
The Defense Ministry did not launch a tender for the purchase and negotiated directly with EADS.
The current defense directorate claims that the exchange promotes the future export of L-159 abroad.
The Czech army acquired 72 aircraft from Aer and only uses 24, so it wants to sell the rest.
The purchase of Casa aircraft may have legal consequences.
The European Commission has already denounced the Czech Defense Ministry before the European Court of Justice because it should choose the aircraft by conducting a European tender and not contacting a single manufacturer.
The army has already received three Casa planes and the last one is due to arrive at Prague&#39;s Kbely airport in fourteen days.
An index finger longer than the ring finger indicates a lower risk of cancer
Men who have a longer index than the ring finger are at a lower risk of prostate cancer.
