The democratic routine
Support for democracy in Latin America continues to grow, as does support for private companies.
Crime is of greater concern than unemployment.
Furthermore, in much of the region, Brazil is seen as a more influential country than the United States.
These are some of the conclusions of the latest Latinobarometer survey conducted in 18 countries and published exclusively by The Economist.
Since the survey has been conducted regularly since 1995, it allows for monitoring of attitudinal changes in the region.
Two related issues stand out in the results of this year&#39;s survey, conducted in September and early October.
The first is the relatively lively humor that prevails in Latin America.
The second is the increasing stability of attitudes towards democracy and its main institutions.
Support for democracy has increased considerably in several countries on the Pacific coast of South America (see Table 1).
For example, in Peru, where economic growth has averaged 6% per year since 2002, support for democracy has risen from a reduced 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
It also grew in Mexico, where the economy has recovered after suffering a large decline in production last year.
However, only half of the respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the two most populous countries in the area, are convinced Democrats, which is lower than the regional average (see figure 2).
About 44% of respondents in the region said they were satisfied with the way democracy works in practice in their country, the same figure as last year, but considerably higher than the 25% registered in 2001 (Figure 3).
Around 34% said they trust their country&#39;s Congress and 45% their government, the same amount as last year in both cases, but considerably higher in relation to 2003 (17% and 24%, respectively).
A decade ago, economic turmoil in Latin America seriously affected support for democracy.
The fact that it has persisted during the global financial crisis is probably due to the fact that many Latin American countries were only affected by a brief recession and enjoyed a strong recovery.
In addition, the existence of a stronger social safety net has contributed to protecting the poorest.
(The United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America reported this week that the proportion of Latin Americans living in poverty increased only marginally in 2009 and has dropped again this year, to 32%.)
However, the mood varies considerably from country to country (see figure 4).
Brazil&#39;s good economic performance and the popularity of its outgoing president, Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva, is reflected in a general feeling of progress.
Such sentiment is less common in Mexico and Central America, where the recession was more severe and violent crime has increased.
For the second time since the surveys began, more respondents in Latin America cite crime, rather than unemployment, as the most serious problem facing their country (see Figure 5).
About 31% say they or a close relative have been the victim of crime in the last year, a figure that has dropped from 38% last year and is the lowest percentage recorded since 1995.
The more positive economic returns are reflected in greater support for private companies and the market economy: around 71% of respondents in the region say that private companies are essential for development, while in 2007 it was only the 56% (see figure 6).
About 58% agree that the market economy is the only system that will allow their country to develop, up from 47% last year.
Interestingly, 62% of those surveyed in Venezuela think the same (and 80% support private companies), although its leftist president, Hugo Chávez, is expropriating numerous private companies.
Brazil is the country that exercises the greatest leadership in the region, as indicated by 19% of those surveyed (compared to 18% last year), followed by the United States (9%, the same figure as last year) and Venezuela (9% compared to 11% a year ago).
However, the United States is considered the most influential country by respondents in Mexico and much of Central America, while Venezuela holds such a title in Ecuador, the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
Elections thrown away
No one expected the general elections held on November 28 in Haiti to be perfect.
However, they went far worse than foreigners trying to help the country come back from its troubles feared.
Votes were entered in the polls, some people voted several times, ballots thrown in the gutters, polling stations destroyed, and acts of intimidation.
Polling stations opened hours late.
Many Haitians, including groups displaced by the January earthquake, roamed the area trying to figure out where to vote.
Some of them, in the end, gave up.
A dozen presidential candidates, including several of the most popular, denounced fraud and called for the election to be annulled.
The protests, some of them violent, spread across the country.
Nonetheless, Edmond Mulet, the highest ranking United Nations official in Haiti, declared that it was &quot;a relatively good election in many ways.&quot;
Observers from the Organization of American States and the Caribbean Community cautiously stated that &quot;we do not believe that these irregularities, no matter how serious, necessarily invalidate the process.&quot;
In other words, the show goes on.
The electoral authority, which according to its opponents is beholden to René Préval, the unpopular outgoing president, and his candidate, Jude Célestin, should announce the preliminary results on December 7.
The tiebreaker is expected to take place in January.
All hope regarding the elections has not yet been lost.
The two main opposition candidates, Michel Martelly, a rapper, and Mirlande Manigat, a former first lady, have withdrawn their initial petition calling for the invalidation of the vote.
But problems can still arise if the electoral authority declares that Mr Célestin, who has little, if any, support has advanced to the second round.
Considering that the cholera epidemic is sweeping the country and more than a million of the survivors of the earthquake continue to live in tents, a large abstention is expected.
Eventually, many Haitians wanted to vote but were unable to do so due to a lack of organization.
Around 250,000 identity documents, necessary for voting, had not yet been distributed shortly before the elections.
The stakes are high.
Aid donors see the election of a popular and legitimate government as an essential step in rebuilding Haiti.
And, as has become clear, the Haitians themselves think so too.
Tiptoeing to the center
In the weeks that have passed since she lost her husband, Cristina Fernández, the president of Argentina, has enjoyed great sympathy among the public that has increased her popularity rating by 20 points, to more than 50%, the highest level that he has registered since his election in 2007.
Regardless, whether it can turn it into a successful campaign for a second term in next year&#39;s elections will depend on whether the clearly affected Mrs. Fernández sets aside the intransigence of her late husband, her predecessor and political partner, Néstor Kirchner.
And, at this point, the indications are not conclusive.
Mr. Kirchner, who continued to take charge of economic policy even after his wife succeeded him as president, had a habit of drawing up budgets that underestimated tax revenues, economic growth, and inflation.
This allowed the presidential couple to spend the additional income at their discretion.
In theory, Mrs. Fernández&#39;s government lost its majority in Congress last year.
However, the opposition is divided, a situation that has worsened after Kirchner&#39;s death from a heart attack on October 27.
Some dissenting members of the ruling Peronist movement have clashed with Mrs. Fernández.
However, after chaotic sessions in which one deputy punched another in the face and other deputies accused the government of bribery, Congress decided to reject the 2011 budget.
&quot;I am not going to argue,&quot; said the president.
The 2010 budget will therefore be applied to next year, giving the president even more leeway when it comes to spending it.
The economy is improving considerably: it will probably grow as much as 9% this year.
The official inflation rate is currently at 11.1%, but numerous private calculations, in addition to the wage demands of the unions, put it around 30%.
Mr. Kirchner, who came to power in 2003 when Argentina was on the brink of economic collapse, made growth and poverty reduction his priorities, rather than controlling inflation.
He refused to negotiate with the IMF, put pressure on the private sector, and had INDEC, the statistical institute, adapt official inflation statistics.
Will President Fernández now moderate these policies?
He has called meetings between the private sector and union leaders.
In addition, its officials say they want to limit salary increases next year to 18%.
The economy has been boosted by the high prices of Argentine agricultural exports around the world.
However, inflation has limited the growth momentum achieved with a large devaluation in 2002.
Perhaps for this reason Mrs. Fernández is showing signs of wanting to restore Argentina&#39;s financial ties with the rest of the world.
At the beginning of the year, the government reached an agreement with the bondholders who had refused a previous forced restructuring of the debt that Argentina had not paid in 2001.
At present, it seems that Mrs. Fernández is about to conclude an agreement with the creditor governments grouped in the Paris Club, to which she owes around 6.7 billion dollars.
The Kirchners always insisted that this would not imply IMF supervision, as is usual.
However, last month Amado Boudou, the Minister of Economy, announced that the Fund will offer &quot;technical assistance&quot; to develop a new national consumer price index, which seems the prelude to the cleanup of INDEC.
It is not clear if President Fernández wants to continue in politics when her term ends, taking into account that she no longer has her husband by her side.
If he does, he will need to win the support of the middle class, much of which has grown weary of Kirchnerism.
When Argentines return from their summer vacations in March, the wave of sympathy for her will have subsided.
If she wants to win other elections, she will have to decide whether or not to repudiate many of her husband&#39;s policies with ease.
Half hooray for China
Voters in Taiwan are slowly approaching a kind of closer union with the mainland.
What does Taiwan think of its big brother across the strait?
More than 7.5 million voters, 70% of those eligible, turned out on November 27 to elect the mayors and councilors of five urban districts in what appears to be a broad assessment of the president, Ma Ying-jeou.
