An arsenic-resistant microbe raises the possibility of new life forms on Earth ... or elsewhere
The discovery of a strange bacterium that can use arsenic as one of its nutrients expands the possibility of finding new forms of life on Earth and possibly other planets.
Although the researchers discovered the curious bacterium here on Earth, they say it shows that life forms may exist without the main elements they considered essential.
&quot;This organism has a double capacity.&quot;
&quot;It can grow with either phosphorus or arsenic.&quot;
&quot;That makes it very peculiar, although it is close to being a really &#39;alien&#39; kind of life,&quot; said Paul CW Davies of Arizona State University, co-author of the report that appears in Thursday&#39;s online edition of the journal Science.
It has long been considered that there are six major elements essential for life: carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulfur.
However, researchers have found that the bacteria, found in Mono Lake, California, can continue to grow after replacing phosphorus with arsenic.
&quot;It makes you wonder what else is possible,&quot; said Ariel D. Anbar of Arizona State University, a co-author of the report.
According to Anbar, the finding is important for the search for life on planets other than Earth, since researchers need to be able to recognize life, know what it looks like.
The study focuses on a microbe discovered on Earth.
However, the call for a press conference to discuss it, in which details of the discovery were not disclosed, generated much speculation on the Internet about the possibility that the report indicated the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
It did not.
What the discovery &quot;does show is that in other planetary environments, there could be organisms that use other elements to boost their biochemistry and that the set of&quot; standard &quot;elements that we consider indispensable for life may not be so fixed,&quot; said Charles Cockell. , Professor at the Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute, Open University, Milton Keynes, UK.
Cockell was not part of the investigation team.
&quot;This work is novel because it demonstrates the substitution of one element for another in biochemistry and basic biochemical structure,&quot; Cockell added.
The discovery was not made by chance.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of NASA&#39;s Astrobiology Institute, who led the study, focused on Mono Lake because it has high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are chemically similar, so he speculated that a microbe exposed to both could substitute one for the other.
&quot;Arsenic is toxic mainly because its chemical behavior is similar to that of phosphorus.&quot;
&quot;As a result, it can be difficult for organisms to differentiate between them.&quot;
&quot;However, arsenic is different enough that it doesn&#39;t work as well as phosphorus, so it goes in and, so to speak, weighs down the biochemical machinery,&quot; Anbar explains.
The researchers collected the bacteria known as GFAJ-1 and exposed them to increasing concentrations of arsenic, which they adapted to and used to grow.
The microbe grows best on phosphorus, but proving that it can live with arsenic instead raises the possibility that an arsenic-using life form may exist naturally, either in other parts of the world or on another planet. or moon where arsenic is more common.
Jamie S. Foster, assistant professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, said the idea that phosphorus can be substituted for arsenic is not new, but an example has never been found to show that it works.
Arsenic was more common in Earth&#39;s early eras, he noted, so the researchers speculated that early life forms may have used it.
&quot;It does suggest that there might be other means of generating life, not just the way life formed on Earth in ancient times,&quot; said Foster, who was not part of the Wolfe-Simon research team.
The research was supported by NASA, the Department of Energy, and the National Institutes of Health.
