Can civility bridge the gap to bridge the gap?
After a notable campaign of invective and negativity, this week has sparked a bit of civility in Washington.
Is it a harbinger of genuine future bipartisan cooperation or an illusory moment before a quick return to partisan combat in the capital?
Tuesday&#39;s meeting between President Obama and congressional leaders did not produce any progress on the big issues to be addressed during the outgoing session.
But from what everyone is saying, it was at least a polite discussion of the two sides&#39; differences, as well as an acknowledgment of their shared responsibilities to rule, rather than just another empty episode to score partisan points.
Wednesday&#39;s public meeting of the president&#39;s deficit committee was equally civilized, despite remaining political differences among members.
It seems clear that the close interaction over a period of months generated a mutual respect that transcends the ideological gap that still separates the members.
That&#39;s just enough to declare that a new era of cooperation has arrived.
Now both sides are on a probationary period, probing each other for signs of cooperativism and commitment, as they try to assess the limits of public opinion and voters&#39; patience for a renewed partisan war.
Reason why Tuesday&#39;s meeting and subsequent evaluations of it by the participants were made with a minimum of demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too great and too deeply ingrained to suggest any rapid change in climate that has existed over the past two years.
Whether it is taxes, expenses, healthcare, or welfare, the two sides are at opposite poles.
Still, the November election has softened the mood in Washington, at least in the short term.
&quot;There is no question that things have changed in terms of the way you say things,&quot; said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official now at the Center for Ethics and Public Policy.
&quot;They are inevitable after the elections.
The elections arouse party passions, which are later extinguished.
That&#39;s good&quot;.
On some issues, particularly those on the outgoing session agenda, Republicans and Democrats have no choice but to find a solution.
The Bush tax cuts expire at the end of the year, and no one is in favor of this.
Both parties want to find a way to preserve some or all of the reductions, permanently or temporarily.
Similarly, there is likely to be a commitment to expand unemployment benefits, probably because Republicans cannot make believe that they are in favor of tax cuts for the rich, denying unemployment benefits for unemployed workers.
After Tuesday&#39;s meeting at the White House, there is greater optimism for a possible deal on these issues during the outgoing session, along with the ratification of the new START (Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty) nuclear disarmament pact.
But William Galston of the Brookings Institution cautions that successful cooperation on the pressing issues of the outgoing session will not necessarily lead to continued bipartisanship when the new 112th. Congress meets in January.
On the contrary, he affirmed that it is very probable and even inevitable that a period of disagreement will begin.
&quot;After the things that need to be done are carried out, in the short term psychology will revert the situation to one of confrontation,&quot; he said.
Wehner also expressed skepticism (which is widely shared) that civility can lead to true cooperation.
&quot;I see most of what will happen between now and 2012 as a rehearsal for the main event of 2012,&quot; he said.
The reasons have much to do with the constitution of the new Republican majority in the House and the voters of the Tea Party, who were instrumental in its creation.
As aware as Republican leaders are of the dangers of overstating their position, they know they must try to keep their promises to cut state spending and overturn the new healthcare law.
Those party lines are already clearly seen in the initial reactions to the deficit commission&#39;s recommendations, which include reforming the tax code and raising some taxes and the retirement age, and cutting spending.
Co-Chairs Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have taken on one of the toughest jobs in Washington and, by their own estimation, have forced the deficit issue onto the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes on the 18-member commission to publish their plan as an official recommendation, and they have been struggling to get close to that number.
The greatest resistance is among the elected officials on the panel, suggesting that on fiscal matters there is, at least currently, little basis or desire for compromise.
Galston predicts two phases in the battles between Republicans in the White House and those in Congress.
The first will come next year in the form of partisan clashes, when Republicans challenge Obama on the budget, taxes and health care, followed by a period of increased bipartisan cooperation.
What would cause the change?
Public opinion.
There is considerable evidence that despite the partisanship of the recent election, a majority of Americans still want to see the two parties working together.
If the confrontation leads to a stalemate, as it did in 1995, then both parties will carefully watch the reaction of the people.
Whoever they think is losing is likely to change course and seek compromise.
However, this may be an optimistic view.
Partisanship and polarization are greater today than they were in the mid-1990s, and there appears to be a larger ideological gap between Obama and Congressional Republicans than there was between President Bill Clinton and the Republicans at the time.
At the same time, activists from both parties see 2010 as the mere prelude to a more momentous election in 2012.
Given this reality, the civility on display this week can be welcomed by many Americans.
But this will require much more effort on the part of both sides to find common ground on the issues that still divide them.
