During the Khmer Rouge rule of Cambodia, between 1975 and 1979, approximately 1.7 million people were executed or died of hunger, disease or overwork.
When the Vietnamese invaded and overthrew the Pol Pot-led government in 1979, remnants of the regime and its military fled to Cambodia&#39;s border with Thailand.
There they launched an insurrection that lasted until the last movement that surrendered in December 1998.
As Pol Pot, Nuon Chea, and Ieng Sary led the guerrilla warfare from their bases in the mountains and jungles of western Cambodia, Ta Mok cultivated a following in Anlong Veng.
But in the mid-1990s, after a UN-sponsored peace accord led to the country&#39;s first democratic elections in 1993, large groups of Khmer Rouge fighters began to defect to the government, culminating in surrenders of Ieng Sary in 1996, and Nuon Chea and Khieu Samphan in 1998.
Pol Pot died of natural causes in 1998, and Ta Mok, who had resisted, was captured by government forces in 1999 in the nearby Dangrek Mountains.
He died in a Phnom Penh prison in 2006 while awaiting trial.
Without the support of their benefactors, the oldest Khmer Rouge fighters fell into the utter misery common in rural Cambodia, and many are nostalgic for the movement.
Although a few elite Khmer Rouge officials retained their local administrative posts in exchange for laying down their arms, the common soldiers remain poor and unskilled farmers.
&quot;These people have made little profit after the surrender,&quot; said Sok Leang of the Center for Justice and Reconciliation, which offers public forums throughout Cambodia, including in Anlong Veng.
&quot;They have incorporated the utopian agrarian ideology of the regime.&quot;
&quot;They were raised with no concept to do business.&quot;
Sister Lim, 55, who joined the Khmer Rouge as a teenager in 1974, fought in the jungle near Anlong Veng before turning to life as a poor rice farmer in 1998.
&quot;Life with the Khmer Rouge was good,&quot; he said.
&quot;Ta Mok fed everyone.&quot;
&quot;But now life is difficult because we have to provide for ourselves.&quot;
