Early next year, the court is expected to begin prosecuting Nuon Chea, Khieu Samphan, Ieng Sary and his wife, Ieng Thirith, another former Khmer Rouge minister.
The court&#39;s mandate is to prosecute top leaders and those most responsible for the crimes, but it has not said whether it will pursue cases in addition to those four.
This did not do much to ease fears in Anlong Veng.
Recent media speculation has focused on Im Chaem, 64, who was a district chief in Banteay Meanchey province during the Khmer Rouge rule in the late 1970s.
In 2007, she told investigators at the Cambodia Documentation Center that she had supervised the construction of the Trapeang Thma dam, a project in which thousands of forced laborers are thought to have died.
During a recent muggy afternoon, Im Chaem returned from working in the fields to his home on wooden stilts on a dirt road outside Anlong Veng.
