&quot;Cambodia is peaceful and stable,&quot; he said.
&quot;If there are more prosecutions, there will be war.&quot;
Prime Minister Hun Sen, who defected from the Khmer Rouge in 1978, has also repeatedly warned that there will be instability if the court goes after more suspects, although experts and historians question this.
&quot;Cambodia must dig a hole and bury the past,&quot; he said.
But facing the past is exactly what Cambodia must do to move forward, said Chhang Youk of the documentation center.
&quot;Reconciliation, according to Khmer, is putting the broken pieces back together,&quot; he said.
&quot;It is our obligation to put these broken pieces together so that we can understand.&quot;
The center produced the first government-approved textbook on the Khmer Rouge, called &quot;A History of Democratic Kampuchea,&quot; at 75 pages.
