Red Bull triumphs in F1 with a secret weapon from Siemens
A software designs car improvements in real time.
Since Red Bull burst into the world of Formula 1 in 2004, its history in this select universe of speed has been marked by surprise and success.
At first no one took into consideration the options of a newly arrived team and, despite the upward trajectory of the last seasons, last November, in the final stretch of the championship, everyone bet on the triumph of Fernando Alonso&#39;s Ferrari.
Without detracting from the ability as a driver of the finally champion, the German Sebastian Vettel, nor the capacity of the Renault engine that powers his car, in the world of Formula 1 the &quot;secret weapon&quot; that the multinational Siemens has become a legend. has put it in the hands of Red Bull to make it a winning team.
It is actually a powerful process simulation software that the German company put on the market in 2007 for purposes far removed from high-end car competition.
Called PLM, this powerful computing instrument has been used to design assembly lines for manufacturing factories around the world, power plants, high-precision instruments.
The objective is to reproduce and faithfully simulate the product or process before actually building it, thus avoiding avoidable errors and expenses.
PLM has facilitated the development of Canon&#39;s cameras, Sukhoi aircraft or Nissan&#39;s most famous utility cars.
Siegfried Russwurm, head of the industrial division of Siemens, explains that the use of this computerized instrument in its Formula 1 factory has allowed Red Bull to design and carry out &quot;in a few hours, almost in real time&quot;, the modifications, changes and improvements that are detected during the races and in the tests.
Russwurm explains that the teams in 1992 had an average of 10 technicians on their team who were capable of introducing a maximum of three or four improvements to the vehicles during each season.
Today 180 highly qualified young professionals work in the Red Bull team who, equipped with powerful computer equipment, analyze and plan all kinds of modifications to the racing cars.
The Siemens manager explained that the PLM software is capable of analyzing and improving all the elements of Red Bull racing cars with the exception of the engine, which is entirely the responsibility of Renault.
Materials, fuel, aerodynamics and safety elements are modified.
Changes can be brought from simulator virtual reality to reality in less than 24 hours, thanks to advanced laser production systems and high-tech autoclaves.
The only limitation on this madness of technological improvement is the figure of 40 million dollars that each Formula 1 team can spend at most each season to facilitate competition.
Red Bull has set up the high-tech factory to design and produce its racing cars in a town about 50 kilometers from London.
These are two buildings in which visits are restricted, especially for journalists.
Everything that happens there is considered &quot;top secret&quot;.
The staff for this task amounts to 580 people, including its two drivers, the champion Vettel and Mark Webber.
Red Bull&#39;s Formula 1 hero is undoubtedly recent champion Sebastian Vetell.
Among the immense technological resources that the energy drink brand has put at the service of its participation in the circuits, there are other protagonists whose competition is inestimable and their notoriety is null.
The factory&#39;s chief technology officer, Steve Nevey, says that five years ago you could say that R&amp;D advances in wagon cars accounted for 50% of the victories and the drivers were responsible for the rest.
Today these percentages have varied and technology accounts for 85% of the success, while pilots contribute 15% of the added value.
Nevey acknowledges that the Vettel or Webber will never be replaced by computer science as &quot;they are unpredictable gladiators.&quot;
