Shoemaker and the German Red Line
Berlin has chosen to stay in the euro, but has set the conditions for the entire Union.
The tensions in the markets have provoked a double governmental response.
On the one hand, José Luis Rodríguez Zapatero has advanced new adjustment measures, from tax reductions to SMEs, regulation of private placement agencies or suppression of the 426 euros of aid to unemployed without benefits, to the privatization of 49% of AENA, of the management of the Barajas and El Prat airports and 30% of State Lotteries.
On the other, Vice President Elena Salgado, with the support of former President Felipe González, has joined the criticism of Chancellor Angela Merkel for her responsibility in unleashing the current crisis.
How are these movements to be interpreted?
Go ahead that Merkel&#39;s position is not an error in her communication policy.
On the contrary, it is another turn of the screw in the difficult process of redefining the euro.
And there Germany has a radically new vision of what its future should be, which clashes with that of maintaining the old traditions of many of its partners.
Faced with European resistance, Germany is beginning to speculate on the three possible solutions to the crisis.
The first, a strong euro, made up of itself, Austria and the Netherlands, among other countries, while the south would leave the monetary zone.
The second, the recovery of the framework, although it now seems like science fiction, with a very favorable current of opinion, close to 50% of the population.
The third, a redesign of the euro, in line with the German proposals for greater macroeconomic control, budgetary rigor, fines for transgressing countries, possible suspension of payments from some of them and extension to the private sector of the costs of potential adjustments.
The German position is clear and has been defined for a long time, so now there are no excuses.
First, in 2009, when both the IMF and the European Commission stimulated deficits, the German government pulled out a constitutional reform to prevent them from 2016.
This was the first sign of divergence between what Germany believed should be done (plans for fiscal rigor and stability in public finances), and what its European partners, including France, were practicing.
The second on the forehead was given by the Central European country when Merkel painfully lengthened the decision to rescue Greece.
Already then it was the object of fierce criticism, but the truth is that the political consensus in Germany and the public and published opinion were very against the rescue of Greece.
Finally, in the last days of October, again Merkel emerges with a clear position, demanding the reform of the Union&#39;s treaties, to make it possible to rescue a country and, at the same time, force private lenders to run with part of the cost.
This position has been interpreted as anti-European, having precipitated the Irish crisis and everything else.
But his proposal, although somewhat sweetened, has been approved and, in the coming months, we should attend the Union reform process that makes those measures possible as of 2013.
Germany has drawn a red line that it does not intend to cross.
And he is telling us all that, although now we have to take measures with which he may not agree very much, as of that date the old functioning of the euro will be over.
2013 will mean the birth of a new monetary area, in which the offending countries will be severely sanctioned, they can be forced to declare themselves in suspension of payments and, in that case, the private sector will also bear part of the cost.
Germany is signaling to us that we must follow a severe growth path with high savings and investment rates, moderation in consumption, improvements in productivity and competitiveness, and positive external balances.
Another alternative based on debt and construction, with huge holes in the balance of payments, like the one that has dominated Spanish growth in the boom years, they simply will not tolerate.
The stake is clear.
And we would be wrong not to understand it.
It is not just about bringing the public deficit back to 3% in 2013.
What they demand of us is much harder.
And the worst thing we could do under these circumstances is fool ourselves.
I hope that the current turmoil will give way to more calm.
And that we take advantage of the window of opportunity that they have given us, until the spring of 2013.
It seems that President Zapatero has also understood it this way and his double manifesto (the reforms promised after last Saturday&#39;s meeting with large companies and yesterday&#39;s announcement of new measures) suggests that, despite criticism of Merkel, it has been opened I walk the thesis that you have to put order at home.
But the red line that Germany has drawn is there, and it does not seem that they are going to move it.
And, among the possibilities that are contemplated, that of leaving a monetary area that is too crowded with not very serious countries, cannot be excluded.
Then Germany can always tell us that it has already warned us.
Sports and law fraud
Tricks like those of Alonso and Ramos against Ajax show ingenuity but not the will to escape a penalty.
The expulsion allegedly concocted by two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the match played on November 23 against Ajax in the Champions League has caused rivers of ink to be written about whether or not such behavior is unsportsmanlike and if, eventually, both players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
As is well known, in the absence of a few minutes to finish the game (which their team had already clearly won), the two players deliberately lost time when taking fouls to cause the referee to show them the second yellow card.
In this way, and since Real Madrid will already finish as the leader of their group, both players will comply with the regulatory sanction the next game of the league, against Auxerre, and will be able to pass clean of cards to the next phase.
Finally, the UEFA disciplinary committee has sanctioned the team&#39;s coach, José Mourinho, with two matches, and the players involved with different financial amounts.
The provocation of a yellow card in circumstances like this or similar is not a new practice, but rather frequent in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos, of the unwritten, but followed, rules of this sport.
Part of the debate that arose in the aforementioned case is due to the fact that it has been carried out by a team of the Real Madrid entity (which in its anthem boasts of nobility and honor, and that on past occasions has fined its players for similar acts) and the dramatization orchestrated, apparently, by Mourinho, who adds one more episode to his long history as a histrionic and provocative technician.
In any case, the debate revolves around whether this type of behavior not expressly prohibited by the regulations contradicts the principles of sport, that is, if these actions commit fraud of the law; Well, in effect, they are actions that are respectful of the sports regulations, but they seem to elude their meaning.
The question is to examine the type of damage they do to sportsmanship.
One of the assets that sports spirit comprises is the physical integrity of the opposing players, an aspect that these actions did not endanger, that is, there was no violent play.
Another of these assets referred to by fair play is to prevent the offending players&#39; team from taking advantage of the opposing team in an unfair way, which did not happen either.
Now, the paradox of the action of the Real Madrid players is that they did not accommodate what we normally characterize as cheating or fraud, since their violation of the rules was not done in secret to try to avoid the sanction, but that precisely his action tried to be the most obvious in order to receive the referee&#39;s punishment.
They waited and gladly accepted the sanction.
Another question is what kind of advantage offenders get on the intentional fouls examined.
Here it seems necessary to verify that the rival is not placed in a disadvantageous situation or benefit is obtained in the same match, since obviously the result of the action means leaving the team itself with fewer players.
And it is not a useful strategy for the next game either, as the club will not be able to count on those players.
The advantage, obviously, is that players will start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future match.
But it is a long-term advantage, with a certain degree of indeterminacy, since the team can be eliminated at the first change, and also with this action the players serve a penalty game and go to the second cycle of cards, in the one that the suspension due to accumulation of cards occurs with one less than in the first cycle.
So, going through rounds, it is not so clear that it is an advantage.
Ultimately, these actions do not go against sportsmanship, which is part of making strategic decisions that favor making the most of what the rules allow.
In the case at hand, the players did not act to evade the application of the penalty (this would be a clear case of fraud), but rather chose when to submit to it.
They made a strategic decision without avoiding punishment or running away from it.
Although the border between ingenuity and fraud is blurred, this time I think it was a clear case of ingenuity.
The controversy, it seems to me, arises from two factors: because it was about two self-expulsions and because of the way in which the transmission of the directive to provoke them was carried out.
The damage done to the principles of sport by these actions is not so much ethical as it is aesthetic.
