China Maintains Greenhouse Gas Reduction Targets
The representative of that country at COP16 assured that his country has made enormous efforts to reduce its carbon footprint and detailed that it supports its offer to reduce its greenhouse gas emissions by 40 to 45 percent by 2020.
China maintains its offer to reduce its greenhouse gas emissions by 40 to 45 percent by 2020, said Su Wei, that country&#39;s representative at COP16.
In his first public appearance at the 16th Conference of the Parties to the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change (COP16), Su Wei assured that his country has made enormous efforts to reduce its carbon footprint and to reconvert its industry.
In fact, he stated, in the last four years his country has invested 245 million dollars in efforts to reduce the emission of greenhouse gases.
However, he made it clear that China will not change its objectives, but will continue to work together with the international community on this matter.
He said that the Chinese strategy on climate change is divided into four areas: dialogue; capacity building; institution building and support for pilot programs.
Progress has been made in all these areas, including the approval, last year, of a new Energy Law, which includes the objectives set in terms of reducing gas emissions, he explained.
On the other hand, he stressed that in China, federal authorities have been working in coordination with state and local authorities, to achieve the objectives of energy saving, efficient energy use and emission reduction.
In addition, he added, various multi-year plans are underway or have already concluded, both financed by the Chinese government and by governments of other countries.
For example, he referred to the Program for the Efficient Use of Energy, which was implemented during the last five years and which received investments from the United Nations (UN), the government and private initiative.
A provincial climate change project is also underway, another for the exchange of incandescent bulbs for savers and one more for mitigation and adaptation, he explained.
At the same table, Martin Krol, scientific advisor to the government of that country on climate change, said that China&#39;s efforts have been greater than is generally thought.
For example, he stated, the per capita emission of greenhouse gases in China is six tons per person, while in the United States it is 100 tons; China is responsible for 9 percent of the historical contribution in pollution.
Likewise, it has made unprecedented efforts in the use of energy, such as increasing energy efficiency by 20 percent in the last five years and plans to do the same by 2020, he added.
