EU changes rules to obtain visa
People should go to the Visa Applicant Service centers before their interview at the Consular Section; the cost will be lower and so will the waiting time.
As of January 10, 2011, the procedure for processing a visa at the United States Embassy and consulates will change.
With the new procedure, most applicants will have to go to the Visa Applicant Service Centers (ASC) prior to their interview at the Consular Section.
The ASC staff will take the biometric information of the applicant, which will be reviewed by the Consular Section before the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages for applicants, among which are:
The total cost of processing the visa will be lower, it will no longer be necessary to make a payment to make the appointment, another payment to process the visa application and another one for the courier service to deliver the document.
The applicant will only make a single payment that will cover the three services.
The current fee will remain unchanged: the equivalent of $ 140 for a tourist visa, $ 150 for petition-based visas (including temporary worker visas), and $ 390 for merchant and investor visas.
People who wish to renew their visa will not have to attend an interview with the Consular Officer, but will only go to the nearest ASC where they will present their documents and have their fingerprints taken.
Because the biometric information will be collected at the ASC, applicants who require a second appointment to be interviewed at the Consular Section will stay there for less time than in the past.
Likewise, those who request a visa at the Consulates in Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay the extra service fee of $ 26.
For additional information on the new procedure to apply for a visa, visit the following page http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
