Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
It is the equivalent of 70% of the emissions of the planetary automobile fleet.
In Copenhagen last year, major emitting countries such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed to voluntary reduction plans that were to cut global GHG emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
However, a further 5 Gt of this amount should be reduced to stabilize, before 2020, the increase in temperatures by two degrees Celsius to prevent it from getting out of control.
In incandescent bulbs, 95% of the energy is dissipated as heat and the rest, that is, 5%, produces light.
In the case of fluocompact bulbs, energy consumption is reduced by 75% and with the new LED bulbs, energy consumption is reduced even more by two times.
Fluorescent light bulbs last an average of 6,000 to 10,000 hours.
The new LED bulbs, like the ones launched by the manufacturer Philips this week (a company that also participated in the UN study), have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than a incandescent light bulb, which allows us to get an idea of the savings that can be achieved with the replacement plan that would be applied in one hundred countries.
These new bulbs can also be powered by rheostats and emit very little heat.
Above, they do not contain any mercury.
Various specialists have expressed their reservations regarding CFLs, since they contain mercury and must be disposed of as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries, unless manufacturers provide instructions.
However, the report indicates, the main source of mercury emission on the planet is not fluocompact bulbs, but coal-fired power plants, which emit a large amount of mercury to produce the electricity that is wasted with incandescent bulbs.
In the United States alone, these plants emit 25,000 tons of mercury per year.
The report details the advantages that this international program would offer to each country.
For example, Indonesia would thus save one billion dollars a year in electricity and eight million tons of CO2, that is, the equivalent of 3.5 thermal power plants that would cost it 2.5 billion to build.
