The unemployment rate remains stable in France in the third quarter
According to the International Labor Organization (ILO), the unemployment rate in France has remained stable at 9.3% in continental territory (9.7% taking into account overseas departments), as indicated by data corrected with provisional seasonal variations (CVE) published on Thursday by Insee.
The number of unemployed stands at 2,631,000 in mainland France.
The data for the second quarter have been confirmed, 9.3% of the active population in continental territory and 9.7% with the DOM.
In one year, the unemployment rate has registered an increase of 0.1 points.
Overall, 3.4 million people in metropolitan France were not working in the third quarter, but want to work, whether or not they are available in the two weeks for work and whether or not they are looking for a job.
The situation of young people present in the labor market has continued to worsen, with a further increase in the unemployment rate to 24.2% in mainland France (+0.9 points in three months, +0.5 points in one year ), 25% including DOMs.
During the third quarter, 637,000 young people between the ages of 15 and 24 were unemployed in the ILO sense.
For its part, there has been a slight increase in unemployment among the elderly, up to 6.4% in mainland France (+0.2 points in both three months and one year), that is, 482,000 people from over 50 years, a figure that rises to 6.6% with DOMs.
Stability of unemployment has only been recorded among people aged between 25 and 49, with 8.3% in mainland France (-0.1 points in three months, +0.1 points in one year) and 8.8% throughout France.
The Insee has not published the monthly unemployment rate since 2006, after a controversy over its calculation methods.
Eurostat, the statistical agency of the European Union, continues to do so and announced on Tuesday a rate of 9.8% for France (DOM included) in October, after 9.9% in September.
