Snowfall continues to cause traffic difficulties, especially on the secondary network in Brittany, and can affect various economic activities.
Twenty-four departments are currently on orange alert due to the risk of snowfall and ice formation.
Eure, Eure-et-Loir, Deux-Sèvres and Vienne have joined the twenty departments that were already on orange alert, eighteen from Wednesday noon and two, Dordogne and Gironde, joined the group at night.
According to Météo France, the heavy snowfalls affect the north of Gironde and Charentes, although it also snows slightly in the Ile-de-France.
Snow layers of between 2 and 5 cm, specifically between 7 and 10 cm, are expected in the affected departments, and between 1 and 3 cm, or even up to 5 cm, in the Paris region.
The departments affected are Charente, Charente-Maritime, Côtes d&#39;Armor, Finistère, Gironde, Dordogne, Poitou and those of the Lower Normandy, Ile-de-France and Limousin regions.
The snowfalls are strong enough to cause circulation difficulties and affect some economic activities, alert Météo France.
In the Côtes d&#39;Armor, access to several departmental roads has been banned for heavy vehicles over 7.5 tonnes, including the Guingamp-Lannion and Saint-Brieuc-Loudéac axes.
According to the gendarmes, the circulation in the secondary network of Brittany is complicated, reason why they recommend that it is not driven except in case of necessity and has prohibited the circulation of certain TER vehicles during the day.
During Thursday, school transport has been banned in Picardy.
No specific measure was planned on Wednesday night to limit the movement of heavy vehicles.
The prefecture &quot;urges all drivers to drive with the greatest care on the roads and to adapt their driving to the situation.&quot;
The Directorate-General for Civil Aviation (DGAC) asked airlines to cancel 25% of their flights at Roissy Paris airport and 10% at Orly on Thursday because of the expected snowfall.
The DGAC recommends air passengers to contact their airline.
In Great Britain, Gatwick airport, south of London, and Edinburgh airport, in Scotland, are closed until Thursday morning.
