Avenging hackers and diligent spies
The WikiLeaks subject has a double value.
On the one hand, it reveals an apparent scandal, a scandal that only seems scandal in the face of the hypocrisy that governs relations between states, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it announces profound changes on an international scale and foresees a future dominated by regression.
But let&#39;s go step by step.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation of the fact that every file created by a secret service (regardless of the nation to which it belongs) consists exclusively of press clippings.
The &quot;extraordinary&quot; American revelations about Berlusconi&#39;s sexual habits only reflect what has been written for months in any newspaper (except those belonging to Berlusconi) and the sinisterly ridiculing profile of Gaddafi has long given ideas to artists from cabaret to create your skits.
The rule that secret files should only consist of public knowledge news is essential to the dynamics of the secret services, and not only in this century.
If you visit a bookstore dedicated to esoteric publications, you will see that each work repeats (about the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Château, the Templars or the Rosicrucians) exactly what had been written in the previous works.
This is not only because the authors of occult texts do not want to do unpublished research (or do not know where to look for news about the non-existent), but because those who dedicate themselves to the occult not only trust what they already know, which reconfirms that that they had already learned.
This is the mechanism of Dan Brown&#39;s success.
The same applies to secret files.
The informant is lazy, just as the head of the secret services is lazy (or has little anxiety) (if it could not be, I do not know, editor of the Libération), who only considers true what he can recognize.
The top secret information about Berlusconi sent by the American embassy in Rome to the State Department was the same as that published by Newsweek the previous week.
So why have the disclosures of these files caused such a stir?
On the one hand, they only say what every cultured person already knows, that is, that embassies, at least since World War II and since Heads of States can call each other or take the plane to meet for dinner, have They have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of some limited representation exercises, they have been transformed into centers of espionage.
Any viewer who watches investigative films knows it perfectly, we just pretend that we don&#39;t know it out of hypocrisy.
In any case, repeating it publicly violates the duty of hypocrisy and casts a bad light on American diplomacy.
Second, the idea that any hacker could consult the most secret secrets of the most powerful country in the world greatly affects the prestige of the State Department.
Therefore, the scandal affects both the victims and the &quot;executioners&quot;.
But let&#39;s get into the true nature of what happened.
Formerly, in Orwell&#39;s time, it could be conceived at full power as a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
Orwell&#39;s prophecy has come true since, being able to control every movement thanks to the telephone, every transaction made, hotel visited, highway taken, the citizen thus became a complete victim of the eye of power.
But when it is shown, as it is now, that not even the crypts of the secrets of power cannot escape the control of a hacker, the control relationship ceases to be one-way and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen (at least the hacker, chosen as the avenger of citizens) can know all the secrets of power.
How can a power be endured that can no longer even keep its own secrets?
It is true, as Georg Simmel already said, that a true secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); It is also true that all knowledge about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is actually an empty secret, without a secret, since it comes from the public sphere; but revealing, as WikiLeaks has done, that Hillary Clinton&#39;s secrets were empty secrets means taking away all power.
WikiLeaks has not done any harm to Sarkozy or Merkel, but it has done a lot of harm to Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this wound inflicted on such a powerful power?
It is clear that, in the future, States will no longer be able to put any confidential information online, since it would be like posting it on a billboard in the middle of the street.
But it is also clear that with today&#39;s technologies, you cannot expect to have confidential conversations over the phone.
Nothing is easier than discovering if and when a Head of State has traveled by plane and has contacted one of the counterparts.
How will they be able to maintain private and confidential relationships in the future?
I know perfectly well that, for the moment, my forecast is something of science fiction and, therefore, fictional, but I imagine government agents who move discreetly on errands with uncontrollable itineraries, carrying messages that have been learned by heart or, at most, hiding some information written on the heels of their shoes.
That information is then kept, in a single copy, in locked drawers: after all, the Watergate spy attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
In the past, I have written that technology currently advances like a crab, that is, backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized communications, the Internet has re-created a corded (telephone) telegraph.
Videotapes (analog) had allowed film researchers to study a film step by step, going back and forth, discovering all the secrets of editing, whereas now (digital) CDs only allow us to go forward or backward from chapter to chapter , that is to say, to enormous proportions.
With high-speed trains, we can go from Rome to Milan in three hours, while by plane, with the displacements that it entails, we need three and a half hours.
Therefore, it is nothing out of the ordinary that politics and communication techniques lead us back to horse-drawn carriages.
One last comment.
In the old days, the press tried to understand what was secretly up to embassies.
Currently, it is the embassies that request confidential information from the press.
Climate: France&#39;s botches in its financing promises
One year after the Copenhagen Accord, it is time to examine whether the promises of rapidly unlocked financing (called fast start or early) made by developed countries have been honored.
And the French bungling has been revealed.
In the Copenhagen Accord, developed countries pledged to provide $ 30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union pledged to contribute 7.2 billion euros over three years and France 1.26 billion euros (that is, 420 million per year).
During the opening of COP16, the EU put its best cards on the table to convince its partners that its commitment to fast start financing is true: a report detailing the measures of its Member States, a press conference, a great complementary event, the distribution of brochures ...
The transparency operation resulted appreciable and was appreciated for what it is really worth: developing countries and civil society would like all developed countries to do the same and with the same level of precision.
The EU announces that it has released € 2.2 billion in 2010, putting it on the right track towards meeting its € 7.2 billion commitment in 2012.
But if we study the situation in detail, things are more complicated.
According to the Copenhagen Accord, the money must be &quot;new and additional&quot; to ensure that a complementary effort is made, without undermining official development assistance.
Unfortunately, no agreement has been reached on what &quot;new and additional&quot; means.
When the European Commission proposed harmonization, some Member States, including France, have blocked the procedure.
Currently, everyone chooses the reference that best suits them.
For example, the European Commission has taken the year 2009 as a reference: international financing is maintained and 150 million are added in three years as fast start financing.
Other countries have chosen similar benchmarks for the year or level of official development assistance.
By contrast, France considers the funding for &quot;all new projects&quot; in 2010 to be &quot;new and additional&quot;.
In other words, no reference is made to expenditures in previous years or to the total level of official development assistance.
In particular, the total amount of France&#39;s aid to developing countries may remain stable (or even decrease), while pretending that it respects its commitment to &quot;new and additional&quot; funds ...
Another crucial element, the distribution between grants and loans.
Once again, there is no rule and everyone chooses the method of calculation.
Some, like France, consider that each euro loaned is equal to one euro donated.
Obviously, such a thing is difficult to justify: the effort is not comparable.
Although the use of loans may be justified for certain investments that are profitable (frequently, projects related to the reduction of emissions that are based on more efficient technologies), it is fallacious to present a euro to be recovered as equivalent to a euro to be recovered. donate ... At most, only the cost of the loan for the country granting the loan (that is, the equivalent of an interest rate) should be computed for your commitments.
But France does not find such reasoning useful: it &quot;respects&quot; its commitment of 420 million euros by making 91.5% loans (389.8 million euros) and 8.5% donations (36.1 million euros) ; Check out the EU document to see for yourself.
It is the only country in the Union that uses the loan so frequently.
Germany uses it 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia, among others, respect their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the majority of the European Union contributes one euro to fulfill its commitment, France contributes only ten cents and considers that the effort is comparable.
A good trick!
In short, in its fast start financing, France makes a double abuse: on the one hand, in relation to actions over time and, on the other, in relation to the true financial effort.
Spending just € 36.1 million, she manages to give the impression that she is spending 420 million &quot;new and additional&quot;, just as she had promised.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that it is Bercy who has dealt with the arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why would the other Member States continue to donate when they can simply lend?) And in negotiations, since developing countries are not stupid ...
The early finance chapter is a relatively short-term minutia in relation to the climate negotiations as a whole.
But it could be one more grain of sand in the immense machinery that is the UNFCCC.
Hopefully not.
Whatever it is, it is essential to learn from this first year of early financing.
First, France could announce a change in its calculation method for the years 2011 and 2012, with the intention of respecting its commitments and in the same way as the other countries of the European Union.
But especially, France could advance the discussions on the stakes in relation to long-term financing (another essential chapter currently under discussion): we will not get rid of the question of &quot;additional character&quot; and the method of compute loans.
France could change its stance to become as progressive on this issue as it is on others.
Therefore, we are left with the hope of the new Minister of the Environment, Mrs. Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement about France&#39;s fast start-ups and their vision of &quot;extra character&quot; and the use of loans would help to improve the level of international confidence needed to move the negotiations forward.
Warning about pesticides ingested by children
A 10-year-old boy ingests 81 different chemicals in a day, according to a study published on Wednesday by the association Générations Futures (the ancient movement for the rights and respect of future generations).
The association, which warns that its results &quot;do not have a significant statistical value taking into account the limited number of samples analyzed, but are illustrative of the problem dealt with&quot;, purchased the food that is usually used in supermarkets in Oise and Paris between July and September. to consume a child of about ten years in four meals and a snack a day.
These model meals, which respect official recommendations (five parts of fresh fruits and vegetables, three of dairy products and 1.5 liters of water per day), as well as the sweets, were tested in laboratories for chemical substances , pesticides, heavy metals and other pollutants.
The balance of the dish is overwhelming: 81 chemical substances, of which 42 classified as possible or probable carcinogens and five substances classified as safe carcinogens, as well as 37 substances capable of acting as endocrine disruptors (EP), according to studies by various institutions such as the International Cancer Research Center.
&quot;Although, in almost all cases, the legal limits for each individual chemical are not exceeded, our study clearly shows that the exposure of consumers to possibly carcinogenic pollutants and / or PE is of concern&quot;, indicates the association.
For breakfast, butter and milk tea alone contain more than a dozen possible carcinogenic residues and three considered safe carcinogens, as well as around twenty residues that can harm the hormonal system.
The apple, imported from Brazil, intended as a school snack, contains traces of six chemicals, including a fungicide banned in France.
The same applies to Kenyan green beans, included in the food, in which the study has detected traces of a powerful insecticide banned in the EU.
Additionally, Russian steak, canned tuna, and even loaf of bread or chewing gum were flavored with pesticides and other chemicals.
In tap water, tests found nitrates and chloroform.
At dinner, the salmon slice was the most &quot;nutritious&quot; with 34 chemical residues detected and even the analysis of the plastic plate used to heat food in the microwave was not completely clean.
The ultimate risk that these &quot;pollutant cocktails&quot; pose to the consumer &quot;is probably underestimated,&quot; the study says.
The Alliance Europe Ecology-Les Verts (EE-LV), for its part, has proposed &quot;given the gravity of the situation&quot; to apply a moratorium on the use of pesticides to stop &quot;the increase in diseases associated with civilization.&quot;
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Agency (EFSA) indicated the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruit and vegetables consumed in Europe, of which 76 in cereals.